<h2>Santa Ana Winds — Why RSM Gets the October d80 Pattern</h2>
<p>Rancho Santa Margarita sits at the base of the Santa Ana Mountains — the wind comes from the northeast, funnels down Trabuco Canyon and Tijeras Creek, and hits RSM directly. October through December brings multiple strong wind events per month, with gusts exceeding 50mph in Dove Canyon and Robinson Ranch during major events.</p>
<p>The dryer effect: a clean exterior vent cap before a Santa Ana can be 40–50% restricted after a single overnight wind event from dry chaparral, mountain oak leaves, and eucalyptus debris. The dryer runs against that restriction. If the restriction persists for a few weeks of normal use on top of that, the thermal fuse blows. This is the October or November d80 call — the machine ran fine all year, then stopped heating after the first big wind event of fall. We see this pattern every year in RSM and come prepared for it. Annual September vent cleaning plus post-Santa Ana cap checks eliminate this call almost entirely.</p>

